Model Optimization. Fine-tuning not only allows us to optimize an LM on the searched output but also enables adding new words to the model's vocabulary as this has been shown to be a bottleneck for fact prediction. We fine-tune relation-specific LMs and for vocabulary extension, we add a {{2303.11082_FO0022||FO}} of {{2303.11082_FO0023||FO}} objects per relation. For fine-tuning the masked language model objective [bert] is used as well as our training splits. We show results on two setups: 1) fine-tuning {{2303.11082_FO0024||FO}}, denoted {{2303.11082_FO0025||FO}}, and 2) fine-tuning {{2303.11082_FO0026||FO}} and with extended vocabulary, denoted {{2303.11082_FO0027||FO}}. In Table (ref) the model optimization shows the biggest improvements. Only developedBy, producedBy, headquarteredIn deteriorate at first in the {{2303.11082_FO0028||FO}} setup, but producedBy and developedBy improve significantly in the {{2303.11082_FO0029||FO}} setup. We found that after fine-tuning the model predicts substrings that match the ground truth object, e.g. in relation producedBy ``Len`` is predicted if the ground truth object is ``Lenovo`` or ``Xiao`` for ``Xiaomi``. The same happens in relation developedBy, e.g. ``Core`` for ``Corel``, and in relation headquarteredIn e.g. ``Wind`` for the city ``Windhoek``. After vocabulary expansion previously missing tokens like ``Xiaomi`` can now be fully predicted, so that {{2303.11082_FO0030||FO}} can increase in the {{2303.11082_FO0031||FO}} setup. It is worth noting that producedBy and developedBy could only be improved significantly by expanding the vocabulary during fine-tuning. Only for headquarteredIn the precision does not improve. While headquarteredIn does degrade in precision, fine-tuning with an extended vocabulary increases the overall quality significantly (see Table (ref), AVG {{2303.11082_FO0032||FO}}).